<div class="post">
  <h2><a href="/blog/2011/08/19/pricing-for-brightbox-cloud-and-last-call-for-private-beta/">Pricing for Brightbox Cloud (and last call for private beta)</a></h2>

  <p>In preparation for the official launch (more on that to follow soon), we‚Äôre announcing the close of the private beta phase of Brightbox Cloud.</p>

<p>We‚Äôve had around 750 beta testers taking part in the <a href="http://beta.brightbox.com/beta">private beta programme</a> and we‚Äôre grateful to all those who submitted bugs, provided feature requests, and gave both postive and negative feedback. We‚Äôre also grateful to those who built web crawlers, TOR exit nodes etc and generally gave things a good hammering :)</p>

<p>Private beta testers get free cloud resources to play with as well as a 50% discount for the first 3 months when we ‚Äúgo public‚Äù.  We‚Äôll be closing private beta registration on <strong>25 August 2011</strong> so this is the final call:  <a href="http://beta.brightbox.com/beta">sign up for the private beta</a> before it‚Äôs too late!</p>

<h3 id="brightbox-cloud-pricing">Brightbox Cloud Pricing</h3>

<p>Now, the bit we‚Äôve all been waiting for‚Ä¶ I&rsquo;m excited to announce provisional pricing for our new cloud offering.</p>

<p>Brightbox Cloud is a metered service, with resources charged by the hour or by the gigabyte. These new prices do not affect our existing unmetered <a href="http://www.brightbox.co.uk">Rails hosting platform</a> ‚Äì Brightbox Cloud is a completely separate platform.</p>

<h4 id="cloud-servers">Cloud servers</h4>

<p>Cloud Servers are billed by the hour, depending on the ‚ÄúServer Type‚Äù which defines the RAM, disk size and CPU allocation of the server.</p>

<table>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <th>Server Type</th>
      <th>RAM (MB)</th>
      <th>Disk (GB)</th>
      <th>CPU cores</th>
      <th>Price per hour</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Nano</td>
      <td>512</td>
      <td>20</td>
      <td>2</td>
      <td>¬£0.025</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Mini</td>
      <td>1024</td>
      <td>40</td>
      <td>4</td>
      <td>¬£0.05</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Small</td>
      <td>2048</td>
      <td>80</td>
      <td>4</td>
      <td>¬£0.10</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Medium</td>
      <td>4096</td>
      <td>160</td>
      <td>8</td>
      <td>¬£0.20</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Large</td>
      <td>8192</td>
      <td>320</td>
      <td>8</td>
      <td>¬£0.40</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h4 id="load-balancers">Load Balancers</h4>

<p>Load Balancers are billed by the hour. Internet data in and out of Load Balancers is billed at the normal price. Each Load Balancer is highly available within a Region ‚Äì designed to tolerate the loss of an entire Zone. Each Load Balancer supports multiple protocols and, at present, can handle 6000 concurrent connections (additional scaling options will be available soon to handle higher levels of traffic).</p>

<p>Price per load balancer instance (HA) = ¬£0.04/hour</p>

<h4 id="cloud-ips">Cloud IPs</h4>

<p>Cloud IPs are instantly re-mappable public IP addresses which can be mapped to any Cloud Server or Load Balancer within a Region. Each Cloud IP allocated to your account is billed by the hour. Cloud IPs can be allocated and released from your account at any time.</p>

<p>Price per Cloud IP allocated to account = ¬£0.0035/hour (Free until 1 October)</p>

<h4 id="data-charges">Data charges</h4>

<p>Internet data is billed by the gigabyte. Usage data is collected every minute by our billing system. Local data transfer, i.e. data transferred within the same Zone, is free-of-charge. Regional data, i.e data transferred between separate Zones, is free-of-charge until 1 Dec 2011.</p>

<p>Internet data (inbound) = ¬£0.08 per GB<br />
Internet data (outbound) = ¬£0.12 per GB<br />
Regional data transfer = ¬£0.01 tbc (Free until 1 Dec 2011)</p>

<h3 id="any-questions">Any questions?</h3>

<p>If you‚Äôve got any questions about the pricing or anything else about the new cloud platform, <a href="&#109;&#097;&#105;&#108;&#116;&#111;:&#098;&#101;&#116;&#097;&#064;&#098;&#114;&#105;&#103;&#104;&#116;&#098;&#111;&#120;&#046;&#099;&#111;&#046;&#117;&#107;">&#100;&#114;&#111;&#112;&#032;&#117;&#115;&#032;&#097;&#110;&#032;&#101;&#109;&#097;&#105;&#108;&#046;</a></p>

  
  <p class="details">
    <span class="date">posted 19 Aug 2011
    
  
    by <a href="/author/jeremy">Jeremy Jarvis</a>
  
    </span>
  </p>
</div><!-- /post -->

      
        <!-- Snippet for displaying a blog post content in paginated page -->
<div class="post">
  <h2><a href="/blog/2011/03/25/ipv6-brightbox-cloud/">IPv6 in the Brightbox Cloud</a></h2>

  <p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1887" title="ipv6 ping" src="http://blog.brightbox.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/bb-ping-cloud-ipv62.png" alt="" width="628" height="128" /></p>

<p>I don‚Äôt have to tell you why IPv6 is important ‚Äì even the mainstream media has finally realised that the pool of IPv4 addresses is exhausted (it‚Äôs not like we needed tarot cards to predict it!). Any modern network must have support for IPv6.</p>

<p>We‚Äôve been concentrating on perfecting IPv4 in <a href="http://beta.brightbox.com/beta">Brightbox Cloud</a> as that‚Äôs the immediate need, but we‚Äôve considered IPv6 since day one of our network designs (over a year ago now!).  Every cloud server will get IPv6 addresses by default (and AAAA dns records of course), so you‚Äôll be able to access your servers directly. We already have this working for our own test servers and we‚Äôll have it in the hands of our customers very soon.</p>

<p>IPv6 will be a ‚Äúfirst class citizen‚Äù in the Brightbox Cloud ‚Äì supported throughout all of our services: Our Cloud Servers, Load Balancers, Firewall, Cloud IPs and of course <a href="https://api.gb1.brightbox.com/1.0/">our API</a>. We‚Äôre currently working on the full implementation but I thought it was worthwhile announcing our plans, since this is such an important aspect of our service.</p>


  
  <p class="details">
    <span class="date">posted 25 Mar 2011
    
  
    by <a href="/author/john">John Leach</a>
  
    </span>
  </p>
</div><!-- /post -->

      

