"␀<div class="grid_18">
  <p class="intro">Straightforward and cost-effective, our pricing offers unrivalled pound-for-pound performance.</p>
</div>

<%= clear %>

<div class="grid_17">
   <p> We don't attempt to baffle you with our own "unique unit based billing" and neither do we require you to top-up your account before you get started. Pay for what you use - it's as simple as that!</p>
</div>

<div class="grid_6">
  <p style="text-align:right"><img src="/images/misc/card_logos.png" alt="Credit Card logos" /></p>
</div>


<%= clear %>

<%= render "pricing_page_nav" %>


<%= clear %>

<section>

<h3 id="cloud_servers">Cloud Servers</h3>

<div class="grid_18 alpha">

<%= render "pricing_servers" %>

</div>

<%= clear %>

<p>Cloud Servers are billed by the hour, to an accuracy of one minute<sup>1</sup>. The price per hour is dependent on the  "Server Type" which defines the RAM, disk size and CPU allocation of the server.</p>


<p class="footnote"><sup>1</sup> Cloud Servers are billed for a minimum of 1 hour for the first hour, and per-minute accuracy thereafter (read <a href="#hour_minimum" class="highlight">why?</a>)</p>
<p class="footnote">All prices exclude VAT at 20% (<a href="#vat" class="highlight">where applicable</a>)</p>

<%= clear %>
</section>


<section>

<%= back_to_top %>
<h3 id="load_balancers">Load Balancers</h3>
  
<div class="grid_18 alpha">
<%= render "pricing_load_balancers" %>
</div>

<%= clear %>

<p>Load Balancers are billed by the hour, to an accuracy of one minute<sup>1</sup>. Internet data in and out of Load Balancers is billed at the [normal price](#data). Each Load Balancer is highly available within a Region - designed to tolerate the loss of an entire Zone. Each Load Balancer supports multiple protocols.</p>

<p>Currently, each Load Balancer is able to comfortably handle 5,000 concurrent connections. Soon, additional scaling options will be available to handle even larger numbers of concurrent connections.</p>

<p class="footnote"><sup>1</sup> Load Balancers are billed for a minimum of 1 hour for the first hour, and per-minute accuracy thereafter (read <a href="#hour_minimum" class="highlight">why?</a>)</p>
<p class="footnote">All prices exclude VAT at 20% (<a href="#vat" class="highlight">where applicable</a>)</p>

<%= clear %>

</section>

<section>

<%= back_to_top %>
<h3 id="cloud_ips">Cloud IPs</h3>

<div class="grid_17 alpha">
  <%= render "pricing_cloud_ips" %>
</div>

<%= clear %>

<p>Cloud IPs are instantly re-mappable public IP addresses which can be mapped to any Cloud Server or Load Balancer within a Region. Each Cloud IP allocated to your account is billed by the hour. Cloud IPs can be allocated and released from your account at any time.</p>

<p class="footnote">All prices exclude VAT at 20% (<a href="#vat" class="highlight">where applicable</a>)</p>

<%= clear %>
</section>

<section>

<%= back_to_top %>
<h3 id="data">Data</h3>

<div class="grid_17 alpha">
  <%= render "pricing_data" %>
</div>

<%= clear %>

<p>Internet data is billed by the gigabyte, aggregated for each account. Data transferred locally within the same Zone is free-of-charge. Data transferred between separate Zones is free-of-charge until 1 Dec 2011.</p>

<p class="footnote">All prices exclude VAT at 20% (<a href="#vat" class="highlight">where applicable</a>)</p>

<%= clear %>

</section>

<%= clear %>

<section>

<%= back_to_top %>
<h3 id="image_library">Image Library</h3>

<div class="grid_17 alpha">
  <%= render "pricing_image_library" %>
</div>

<%= clear %>

<p>The Image Library provides storage for Cloud Server snapshots and uploaded Cloud Server images. Image Library data charges are incurred when a Cloud Server images are downloaded or uploaded.</p>

<p class="footnote">All prices exclude VAT at 20% (<a href="#vat" class="highlight">where applicable</a>)</p>

<%= clear %>
</section>

<%= clear %>

<section markdown="1">
<%= back_to_top %>

<h3>Pricing FAQs</h3>

<div class="qa grid_11 alpha">
<h4>How does billing work?</h4>

<p>All of the products available within Brightbox Cloud are provided on a metered billing basis. Our cloud billing system collects usage data from across our infrastructure every minute and generates invoices monthly in arrears.</p>

<h4>Do I need to make a pre-payment before using Brightbox Cloud?</h4>

<p>No. Unlike many other cloud services, you don't need to make a payment before using Brightbox - you only need to add a valid credit card.</p>

<h4>Which credit cards do you accept?</h4>

<p>We currently accept both Visa and Mastercard.</p>

<h4>Which currencies do you support?</h4>

<p>We only bill in Pounds Sterling (GBP) at present. We may add multi-currency in future.</p>

<h4>When does billing for a Cloud Server or Load Balancer start and stop?</h4>

<p>Billing starts only when the requested resource (e.g a Cloud Server or Load Balancer) becomes "Active" and is ready to use. Billing stops as soon as a "destroy" request is received by the API. In other words, we start billing as late as possible and we stop billing as early as possibly - so that you only pay whilst a particular resource is usable by you.</p>

<div id="hour_minimum">
<h4>Why do you charge a minimum of 1 hour for Cloud Servers and Load Balancers?</h4>

<p>Cloud Servers and Load Balancers consume more resources during the initial creation process (i.e during the first hour of their lifetime). So, to reflect this, when a Cloud Server is created and deleted within the first hour we round this up to 1 full hour of usage.</p>

</div>

</div>

<div class="qa grid_11 push_2 omega">
<h4>Can I make pre-payments?</h4>

<p>Yes, although it's not a requirement, you can make ad-hoc payments to your Brightbox account and maintain a credit balance. When you receive your monthly invoice, your prepaid balance is deducted first and the remainder is then charged to your registered credit card.</p>

<h4>Can I make a payment by BACS/bank transfer?</h4>

<p>Yes, you can make a pre-payment (see above) via BACS/bank transfer, although you must always have a valid credit card registered in your Brightbox account. An administration fee of ¬£25 will be deducted from any amounts you transfer to cover our bank charges and admin fees.</p>

<div id="vat">
<h4>Will VAT be added to my invoices?</h4>

<p>As a VAT-registered UK company, we're required to add VAT to purchases from: (a) EU-based customers without a valid VAT registration number and, (b) all UK-based customers (regardless of VAT status). </p>
 
<p>EU-based customers with a valid VAT registration number registered to their Brightbox account will not be charged VAT. Also, customers based outside of the EU and, therefore, outside the scope of VAT will not be charged VAT.</p>
</div>

<h4>Are there volume discounts available?</h4>

<p>Please [contact our sales team](/about/contact) to discuss volume discounts.</p>


</div>

</section>
<%= clear %>;@˜"(/static/images/misc/card_logos.png/{;{␀"1/posts/2011-01-26-cloud-load-balancers-beta/{;{	;"‡<p>Today, we‚Äôre excited to announce Brightbox Cloud Balancers ‚Äì our new distributed load balancing service which is available right now as part of the <a href="http://beta.brightbox.com">cloud beta</a> programme.</p>

<p>Cloud Balancers make it effortless to add fault tolerance and horizontal scalability to your systems by distributing traffic across a pool of Cloud Servers ‚Äì even within separate Zones.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Scalable ‚Äì </strong>Cloud Balancers use our high performance distributed cloud infrastructure</li>
  <li><strong>Resilient ‚Äì </strong>automate fault tolerance by balancing across Cloud Servers in separate Zones</li>
  <li><strong>Flexible ‚Äì </strong>map Cloud IP addresses onto your balancers</li>
  <li><strong>Familiar ‚Äì </strong>point domain names at your balancers using standard DNS A-records or CNAMEs</li>
  <li><strong>Simple ‚Äì </strong>use our intuitive commandline interface (or <a href="https://api.gb1.brightbox.com/1.0/">REST API</a>) to configure balancers</li>
  <li><strong>Fast ‚Äì </strong>instantly reconfigure any aspect of your existing balancers</li>
  <li><strong>Customisable ‚Äì </strong>configure custom healthchecks for your pool of Cloud Servers</li>
  <li><strong>Extendable ‚Äì </strong>add as many HTTP or TCP listeners you need per balancer</li>
</ul>

<p>If you‚Äôre already part of the cloud beta programme you‚Äôll simply need to install the latest version of the CLI tool (0.10.1) and you‚Äôll be able to create Cloud Balancers straightaway (see the <a href="http://docs.brightbox.com/guides/load_balancers">documentation</a> for instructions).</p>

<p>If you‚Äôre not on the beta programme and would like to be, why not <a href="http://beta.brightbox.com">submit a beta request</a> today? :)</p>

<h4 style="margin-bottom:15px">Check out the screencast‚Ä¶</h4>

<object classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="630" height="410" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" />
<param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" />
<param name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/03zdxQPEnPI?fs=1&amp;hl=en_GB&amp;rel=0&amp;showinfo=0" />
<param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" />
<embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="630" height="410" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/03zdxQPEnPI?fs=1&amp;hl=en_GB&amp;rel=0&amp;showinfo=0" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" /></object>

<h3 style="margin-top:40px">Cloud Balancer Q &amp; A</h3>

<h4 id="how-does-it-work">How does it work?</h4>

<p>Cloud Balancers are managed via the <a href="https://api.gb1.brightbox.com/1.0/">Brightbox API</a> (or using the CLI tool, which uses the API). You create a new balancer, specifying which services should be balanced and to which back end Cloud Servers. The Cloud Balancer is then automatically built, within a minute or so, on top of the Cloud Balancing layer which spans each Zone within a Region. You can then map a Cloud IP onto the balancer and traffic is distributed across your servers according to the policy you define (the default is ‚Äúleast connections‚Äù). The Cloud Servers are continuously monitored according to a ‚Äúhealthcheck‚Äù you specify. Should one of your Cloud Servers become unresponsive it is removed from the active pool of servers until it is ‚Äúup‚Äù again.</p>

<h4 id="how-does-this-compare-to-amazons-elb-elastic-load-balancing">How does this compare to Amazon‚Äôs ELB (Elastic Load Balancing)?</h4>

<p>Brightbox Cloud Balancers offer a number of advantages over Amazon‚Äôs ELB ‚Äì here‚Äôs a few important ones‚Ä¶</p>

<ol>
  <li>Brightbox Cloud Balancers work with Cloud IPs so you can easily map and remap public IP addresses between servers and load balancers.</li>
  <li>With Amazon ELB you are restricted to using only CNAME dns records, so you can‚Äôt use root domains (e.g http://example.com) ‚Äì whereas with Brightbox you can use A-records and use domain names however you wish.</li>
  <li>With Brightbox you can instantly reconfigure any aspect of your existing balancers, whereas in some situations you‚Äôd need to recreate a new ELB load balancer from scratch.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="how-will-pricing-work">How will pricing work?</h4>

<p>We plan to announce pricing information on both this and other Brightbox Cloud services within the next month.</p>

<p>There will be a standard fixed hourly rate for each Cloud Balancer plus a charge for load balanced internet data (per GB).</p>

<h4 id="how-quickly-are-load-balancers-created">How quickly are load balancers created?</h4>

<p>Load Balancers are normally created and handling traffic within 90 seconds.</p>

<h4 id="how-much-traffic-will-a-brightbox-cloud-balancer-handle">How much traffic will a Brightbox Cloud Balancer handle?</h4>

<p>Exactly how much traffic a single balancer can handle depends largely on your application, but they can comfortably handle 6000 concurrent connections as standard. This will also increase dramatically in the near future as we add new scaling features to the Cloud Balancing layer.</p>

<h4 id="what-kind-of-traffic-can-we-balance">What kind of traffic can we balance?</h4>

<p>You can balance most TCP-based protocols. Specifying an HTTP listener adds an &ldquo;X-Forwarded-For&rdquo; header.</p>
